name: Afghanistan
about: Afghanistan's coordinated system for tertiary education covers the entire country and includes public and private universities. The Kankor exam, held annually, determines admission. Applicants can choose five fields of study. Students are assigned based on their scores, with priority given to those who select the respective institution as first priority.

name: Angola
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Albania
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: United Arab Emirates
about: The National Admissions and Placement Office is responsible for processing the applications for admission from students who wish to either receive a scholarship to study abroad or attend a public institution. The applicant must sit for the Emirates standardized test and achieve the score in the specified subjects that meets the eligibility criteria in the desired institution.

name: Argentina
about: In Argentina, a coordinated system is implemented independently in each city for public primary and secondary education. The systems prioritize students based on staff children, siblings, proximity, and parental work. Assignments follow preference order, and in case of ties, a lottery determines admissions. The systems allow applicants to apply to between 2 and 5 institutions.

name: Armenia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Australia
about: The Australian online enrollment system encompasses both primary and secondary schools, functioning at the regional level across two of the seven regions. Parents can apply to up to three schools, guaranteeing placement in either a local public school or a specifically designated one within a shared zone.

name: Austria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Azerbaijan
about: Azerbaijan conducts coordinated exams to determine higher education admission. In the first stage, applicants take tests on Azerbaijani or Russian languages, a foreign language, and mathematics. Majors are grouped into five categories.

name: Burundi
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Belgium
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Benin
about: Benin's coordinated system for public tertiary education operates nationwide. The ranking for the assignment process considers chosen courses of study, university allowance quotas (scholarships, aids), and fully paid titles. After scholarships, partially and fully paid titles are allocated.

name: Burkina Faso
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Bangladesh
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Bulgaria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Bosnia and Herzegovina
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Belarus
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Bolivia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Brazil
about: Brazil implemented the Unique Selection System (SISU) in 2010 to coordinate college applications for federal public universities. Managed by the Ministry of Education, it allocates undergraduate vacancies based on national high school exam scores. Students select one program daily and cut-off scores are determined. On the fourth day, students are matched to programs based on rankings and scores.

name: Botswana
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Central African Republic
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Canada
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Switzerland
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Chile
about: Chile's coordinated system was gradually adopted by some regions, incorporating the entire country in 2020. The system prioritizes siblings, vulnerable students (through quotas), school staff's children and former students. It has two phases, and if students are not assigned to any preference in the second phase they are assigned to a nearby school with places. Lotteries are used to break ties.

name: China
about: The Chinese primary school admission system is largely decentralized into administrative regions and cities for public and private schools. The mechanism, for the most part, consists of randomly allocating vacancies. Common priority criteria include children of martyrs and children of active military personnel.

name: Cote d'Ivoire
about: Cote d'Ivoire has a coordinated system, managed by the National Orientation Commission (CNO), for secondary education level across five regions (Abidjan, Aboisso, Korhogo, Soubré, Yamoussoukro). The assignment is based on choice order, academic performance, and proximity. Places are reserved for low-income students.

name: Cameroon
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Congo, Dem. Rep.
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Congo, Rep.
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Colombia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Costa Rica
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Cuba
about: Cuba has two coordinated systems (universities and technical programs). For university programs, each student may apply to up to 10, and it is the value of the ranking (from the scale value) that is taken into account, not the order in the application. For technical programs, only when there are more applicants than places, some indicator, requirement or instrument is applied to order applicants.

name: Czech Republic
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Germany
about: Germany operates two admission systems: one for medicine and related programs since 1972, and another for volunteer universities since 2012. The medical system has a two-round process, using a Boston mechanism in the first round and DA in the second. In contrast, the volunteer system comprises three rounds: decoordinated, DA-based, and a final round with a serial dictatorship mechanism.

name: Denmark
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Dominican Republic
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Algeria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Ecuador
about: Ecuador has a coordinated system for primary and secondary education. Flag bearers and applicants with special abilities will be guaranteed a place in the educational institution of their choice. For the remaining vacancies, priority will be given to students living in school area. However, if the demand exceeds the capacity, only those students with the best grades will be selected.

name: Egypt
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Eritrea
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Spain
about: In Spain, the assignment of students to public and private subsidized schools is governed by the Immediate Acceptance mechanism. Features common to all regions include the possibility for students to choose several schools and the priority given to factors such as siblings, proximity and family situation. Tie-breaking criteria such as lotteries are often employed.

name: Ethiopia
about: Ethiopia has a coordinated system for tertiary education and it includes all institutions. Students must pass the secondary school leaving exam with a score above 50%, meet annual cut-off points set by the Ministry of Education, and take aptitude tests for successful placements.

name: Finland
about: Finland has a coordinated system for secondary education. The system covers the entire country and includes both public and some private schools. The applicant is selected to the program that is ranked highest and the application points are sufficient for. The algorithm used is a variant of the school-proposing DA algorithm. The tie-breaker rules use student preferences first and then GPA.

name: France
about: France employs a coordinated system, overseen by academies (districts). A coordinated system was first implemented in 2007, but was first implemented online in 2013. Each academy defines how many preferences an applicant can make. Priority criteria are set at national and academic level. At the national level, the main criterion that delivers allocation priority is geographic sectors.

name: Gabon
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: United Kingdom
about: In the UK, different regions have different coordinated admissions systems. School admissions in all UK regions prioritize factors such as proximity, siblings and special needs.

name: Georgia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Ghana
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Guinea
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Gambia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Guinea-Bissau
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Greece
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Guatemala
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: West Bank and Gaza
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Hong Kong
about: Hong Kong's secondary admission system involves two stages. The first stage is uncoordinated (30% of vacancies) and admission criteria are set by schools. The second stage is coordinated, where 10% of vacancies allow unrestricted school choices (up to 3 schools in or outside the school net), and the remaining 90% involve restricted school choices (up to 30 schools within the school net).

name: Honduras
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Croatia
about: Croatia has a coordinated system for all type of secondary schools. The application process occurs in multiple periods. The common element of evaluation include grades in Croatian language, mathematics and the first foreign language. Additional evaluation elements, such as special skills, are taken into account. For programs lasting at least four years, schools may set a point threshold.

name: Haiti
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Hungary
about: Hungary has a coordinated system at the national level. The mechanism uses a scoring system based on secondary school grades, exams, and additional factors. Each student is admitted to the first program on her list where she achieves the score-limit, resembling Gale Shapley's algorithm. When there is a tie between applicants, they are either all accepted or all rejected.

name: Indonesia
about: Indonesia's state-owned universities admit students via the platform Seleksi Nasional Masuk Perguruan Tinggi Negeri (SNMPTN) based on high school records or the computer-based exam. SNMPTN allows two study program choices regionally, and admissions prioritize academic excellence, economic need, and regional balance.

name: India
about: In India, several entrance examinations determine admission to higher education institutions. JEE for engineering courses, NEET for medical programs, CAT for business schools, CLAT for law schools, NATA for architecture courses and AIEEA for agriculture programs. Allocation is usually given on the basis of academic merit and examinations.

name: Ireland
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Iran
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Iraq
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Israel
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Italy
about: Italy has a coordinated system at the national level for primary and secondary public schools. Admission criteria are determined by each school; there are no national-level guidelines for admission criteria.

name: Jamaica
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Jordan
about: Jordan has a coordinated system for public universities. Programs receive applications through the coordinated system or through a direct application to the university (known as parallel admission). Each applicant choose at least five options and a maximum of thirty. Admission is based on a score derived from a secondary education certificate and an entrance exam.

name: Japan
about: In Japan, municipalities have different admission systems, including: free choice: students can attend any school of their choice within their municipality. Block: Municipalities are divided into blocks, and students can attend any school within the block. Adjacent zone: pupils can attend the school of their choice in the adjacent zone while leaving the conventional school attendance zone.

name: Kazakhstan
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Kenya
about: Kenya has a coordinated system for public schools. Candidates are required to choose and rank their preferred schools prior to sitting for the general entrance examination. The selection process is done at four levels: national, extra-county, county or special schools and district. The selection is based on merit, equity and choice of schools made by the applicant.

name: Kyrgyzstan
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Cambodia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: South Korea
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Lebanon
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Liberia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Libya
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Sri Lanka
about: Admission to public universities is made through a coordinated system managed by the University Grants Commission. The admission is coordinated since 1960s. Sri Lanka has a coordinated system for public universities. The system has three types of quotas: merit (40%), district (55%) and disadvantaged district (5%). Z-scores (normalized scores) rank applicants and are calculated for each quota.

name: Lesotho
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Lithuania
about: Lithuania has a coordinated admission system for public institutions. Applicants can register for up to 9 study programs. A competition score ranks applicants based on grades, test scores, and extracurriculars. Applicants are allocated to study programs based on their competition score and the available spots in each program.

name: Latvia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Morocco
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Moldova
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Madagascar
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Mexico
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Macedonia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Mali
about: Mali has a coordinated system for certain public and private schools. Admissions to secondary schools are based on students' grades, their preferences, and school capacity.

name: Myanmar
about: Myanmar has a coordinated system for university admissions. Students graduating from high schools must collect a university admission form. This form requires students to list up to 20 university courses in descending order based on preference. They must return the completed forms at a designated university in their nearest town. Admission is determined by 10th grade exams.

name: Mongolia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Mozambique
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Mauritania
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Malawi
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Malaysia
about: Malaysia has a coordinated system for vocational, technical, boarding, and religious secondary schools. Students can apply via form One or Form Four. Applications for boarding and religious schools are accepted for both Form One and Four, while Form Four students can apply to secondary technical schools, army college, and vocational colleges.

name: Namibia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Niger
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Nigeria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Nicaragua
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Netherlands
about: In the Netherlands, some cities manage admissions through a coordinated process. The length of the application list varies according to the city. In general, priority is given to siblings of enrolled students and depending on the distance to the school.

name: Norway
about: Norway has a coordinated system for all public and some private institutions. Admission to studies takes place on the basis of ranking within quotas. Quota is a specific proportion of the seats that are distributed among applicants who meet specific requirements. Within a quota, applicants are ranked according to their GPA. Applicants with equal GPA are then ranked by age.

name: Nepal
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: New Zealand
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Oman
about: Oman has a coordinated system for tertiary education institutions. Applicants can list an unlimited number of preferences, with a minimum of 12 programs. Assignments are obtained from students' final exam grades and subject requirements, using the deferred acceptance mechanism. Tiebreaker rules vary by program.

name: Pakistan
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Panama
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Peru
about: Peru has two coordinated admission systems. The first one is for primary and secondary public schools at Lima. The second one is only for primary schools and it is implemented at Arequipa, Madre de Dios and Tacna, and plans to expand nationwide. Both systems involve two rounds processes. Lima's system allows only one preference while the other allows multiple preferences without limit.

name: Philippines
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Papua New Guinea
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Poland
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Puerto Rico
about: Puerto Rico has a coordinated system for primary and secondary schools. Priority is given to students remaining in their current school, then to those seeking transfers based on their preferences. Families can list up to three schools per child.

name: Portugal
about: Admission to public education in Portugal operates through a coordinated system. Applicants compete by institution/course pairs. Applicants are ranked according to high school grades, test scores and prerequisites. The process has different phases, in each of which priority groups have their places reserved. Some programs require certain entrance exams.

name: Paraguay
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Qatar
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Romania
about: Romania has a coordinated system for secondary schools. Candidates can participate in the online system in a single county. Allocation is based on the high school admission average: calculated as a weighted average between the overall average at the national assessment exam and the GPA. After the initial assignment, adjustments may occur for twin or triplet candidates.

name: Russia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Rwanda
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Saudi Arabia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Sudan
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Senegal
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Singapore
about: Singapore has a coordinated system for tertiary institutions. Applicants are assessed based on their net aggregate scores, which consider bonus points for achievements in co-curricular activities, language grades, and school affiliation. Priority is given to applicants with higher net aggregate scores, with tiebreakers based on citizenship status and gross aggregate scores.

name: Sierra Leone
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: El Salvador
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Somalia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Serbia
about: Serbia has a coordinated system at the national level. Students may list up to 20 preferences. Twins must submit identical wish lists. Students with disabilities are enrolled based on functionality levels. The software assigns students according to their top preference.

name: South Sudan
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Slovak Republic
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Slovenia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Sweden
about: Swedish school admission systems are coordinated processes at the municipality level. Criteria such as sibling priority, relative and absolute proximity influence the allocation. Independent schools have their own application procedures. In case of high demand, a lottery may determine the allocation.

name: Syria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Chad
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Togo
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Thailand
about: Thailand has a coordinated system for public universities. The system has four rounds: portfolio, quota, admission, and direct admission. In the admission round, which is the core of the system as it includes the general public, applicants can list up to six programs. Prior to 2019, the admission round had coordinated application but no single offer.

name: Tajikistan
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Turkmenistan
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Tunisia
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Turkey
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Tanzania
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Uganda
about: Uganda has a coordinated system at the national level. The Primary Leaving Examinations (PLE) is mandatory. Once the results of the PLE are published, the selection process takes place, with institutions prioritizing candidates based on preferences and performance. However, some top schools have deviated from this process, setting their own cut-off points or admitting students directly for a fee.

name: Ukraine
about: Ukraine has a coordinated system for all tertiary education institutions of the country. When submitting applications, students must indicate if they want to participate in a budget or non-budget tender. Applicants can submit a maximum of five preferences for budget tender. Admission is based on the national multi-subject test.

name: Uruguay
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: United States
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Uzbekistan
about: Uzbekistan has a coordinated system for tertiary education. Each student can apply to only one university and for one discipline within that university. There are no second choices, requiring unsuccessful applicants to wait for the next academic year to reapply elsewhere. Successful applicants are determined by scores of an entrance exam in three subjects relevant to their chosen program.

name: Venezuela
about: Venezuela's tertiary education utilizes a coordinated system. The system has three phases: registration, preliminary results, and final results. Applicants may apply to 6 programs (3 mandatory choices). The ranking index of each student is calculated based on high school grades, socioeconomic factors, territorialization, and student participation.

name: Albania
about: Albania's coordinated system for primary education covers the entire country with online registration through e-Albania. The system allows parents to register first-grade students, selecting the school based on their address and municipality. Applications are processed by educational institutions, which notify applicants electronically of acceptance or rejection.

name: United Arab Emirates
about: In United Arab Emirates, an online application service register students into public schools, from kindergarten to twelve grade. Students must fill out the application and choose one school. Priority shall be given to students living near the applied school.

name: United Arab Emirates
about: In United Arab Emirates, an online application service register students into public schools, from kindergarten to twelve grade. Students must fill out the application and choose one school. Priority shall be given to students living near the applied school.

name: Argentina
about: In Argentina, a coordinated system is implemented independently in each city for public primary and secondary education. The systems prioritize students based on staff children, siblings, proximity, and parental work. Assignments follow preference order, and in case of ties, a lottery determines admissions. The systems allow applicants to apply to between 2 and 5 institutions.

name: Argentina
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Armenia
about: Armenia's coordinated system of higher education includes admission to all institutions in the country. Applicants submit admission applications online. Access requirements established by the government for each profession are followed.

name: Armenia
about: Armenia has a coordinated system for secondary education. The registration is first open (first day) for students with parents employed at the corresponding school or having a sibling attending. Other applicants register on the second day. The online system allows editing applications, including changing the chosen school.

name: Australia
about: Australian tertiary admissions centers (SATAC, QTAC, UAC, VTAC, TISC) facilitate university applications. Applicants can list preferences, with selection rank (ATAR) influencing offers. ATAR is the standard measure of a student’s overall academic achievement in relation to other students. Each center manages admissions for specific regions, allowing multiple preferences.

name: Australia
about: The Australian online enrollment system encompasses both primary and secondary schools, functioning at the regional level across four of the seven regions. Parents can apply to up to three schools, guaranteeing placement in either a local public school or a specifically designated one within a shared zone.

name: Austria
about: Austria has a coordinated system for primary education in Graz. Parents can specify three school choices, with one required to be within a 1,500-meter radius of the residential address. Catholic private schools are also available for selection. In case of high demand, admission criteria are reviewed jointly by the Department for Education and Integration and the school management.

name: Burundi
about: Burundi's secondary education system aims to allocate students to available seats in public and private schools. Students, after passing a required exam, are assigned to schools. The top-performing students are placed in prestigious schools, while the others are assigned by provincial commissions. Special considerations are given to the Batwa community (ethnic minority).

name: Belgium
about: In Belgium there are three geographic-linguistic communities: Dutch, French and German. The Flanders region, which is part of the Dutch community, has a coordinated system with some rules common to all cities in the region, but other rules specific to each city. The following cities are located in the region: Ghent, Antwerp and Brussels. Brussels is part of both the Dutch and French communities.

name: Belgium
about: In Belgium there are three geographic-linguistic communities: Dutch, French and German. The Flanders region, which is part of the Dutch community, has a coordinated system with some rules common to all cities in the region, but other rules specific to each city. The following cities are located in the region: Ghent, Antwerp and Brussels. Brussels is part of both the Dutch and French communities.

name: Burkina Faso
about: Burkina Faso has a coordinated system for tertiary education. It uses the CAMPUSFASO platform for online guidance. Students can apply to several programs, ranking up to 18 options. The assignment process considers the grades obtained in the baccalaureate exam. This system covers public and some private universities.

name: Bangladesh
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Bangladesh
about: Bangladesh coordinated secondary admission system is unified for all types of institutions. A digital lottery will take place after the application process for public and private institutions, separately. Admission to Dhaka government schools is divided into three groups (science, humanities and business). After admission process, students can apply for quotas' extra seats.

name: Bulgaria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Bulgaria
about: Primary school admissions in Burgas city follow a two-stage coordinated system for all types of schools. Applications are based on a points-based ranking system, considering time lived in the school's area, family members affiliated with the school, and preference for the requested school. After the points are calculated, students are accepted based on their scores.

name: Brazil
about: Brazil’s education system is largely decentralized into administrative regions and municipalities. The Ministry of Education defines the guiding principles and framework and coordinates national education policy for all education levels. Most cities' admission process prioritize factors such as residence proximity, siblings in the same school, and disabled students.

name: Brazil
about: Brazil’s education system is largely decentralized into administrative regions and municipalities. The Ministry of Education defines the guiding principles and framework and coordinates national education policy for all education levels. Most cities' admission process prioritize factors such as residence proximity, siblings in the same school, and disabled students.

name: Botswana
about: Botswana's secondary education system allows students to apply to junior government schools after sitting for the Junior Certificate Examination.

name: Canada
about: In Canada, Edmonton and Toronto public schools have their own coordinated system. In Toronto, students can list up to two preferences, while in Edmonton they can only apply for one school. In both cities, priority is given to resident students.

name: Canada
about: In Canada, Edmonton and Toronto public schools have their own coordinated system. In Toronto, students can list up to two preferences, while in Edmonton they can only apply for one school. In both cities, priority is given to resident students.

name: Chile
about: Chile's coordinated system was gradually adopted by some regions, incorporating the entire country in 2020. The system prioritizes siblings, vulnerable students (through quotas), school staff's children and former students. It has two phases, and if students are not assigned to any preference in the second phase they are assigned to a nearby school with places. Lotteries are used to break ties.

name: Chile
about: Chile has a coordinated tertiary education system adopted by most institutions. Students apply for programs, with a limit of 20 options. After a DA algorithm processes the applications, applicants are accepted into a maximum of one program and are also provided preferences for waitlisted options. In case of a tie, additional places are offered.

name: China
about: The Chinese secondary school admission system is highly decentralized into administrative regions and cities for public and private schools. High school admission usually involves two or more rounds of applications, with each city choosing the length of the allowed application list. Priority is usually given to candidates based on their grades and exam results.

name: China
about: University admission in China is determined by the Gaokao (National University Entrance Examination). Universities are grouped into three tiers based on quality. In 2013, a sequential mechanism (a variant of the Immediate Acceptance mechanism) was replaced by a parallel mechanism (the Serial Dictatorship mechanism).

name: Colombia
about: Bogota has a coordinated allocation system in place since 2007 for primary and secondary schools. Applicants can select up to four public or private charter schools. The system takes into account priority criteria such as students with disabilities, vulnerable students and siblings in the school. The system allocates places based on a selection indicator that weights priority characteristics.

name: Colombia
about: Bogota has a coordinated allocation system in place since 2007 for primary and secondary schools. Applicants can select up to four public or private charter schools. The system takes into account priority criteria such as students with disabilities, vulnerable students and siblings in the school. The system allocates places based on a selection indicator that weights priority characteristics.

name: Cuba
about: In Cuba, the coordinated system for secondary education covers basic secondary education and, from grades 10 to 12, includes vocational, regular secondary schools (preuniversitarios), and skill workers schools. Regular secondary schools aim to enroll high-achieving students. There are seats for students that live at the same municipality of a regular secondary school.

name: Czech Republic

name: Germany
about: In Germany, school admission is coordinated at the city level. In Cologne, parents are allowed to apply to up to two schools, while Hamburg allows up to three preferences. Both cities use allocation criteria such as siblings and academic performance.

name: Germany
about: In Germany, school admission is coordinated at the city level. In all cities, students can apply to up to three schools. Berlin uses the immediate acceptance mechanism to assign students, while Frankfurt uses the same mechanism, but allows for manual assignment changes. In both cities, schools choose their own priority criteria.

name: Denmark
about: Denmark has a coordinated national system for tertiary education admissions, divided into two quotas. Quota 1 is based on GPA, while Quota 2 assesses students on other qualifications set by the institutions. Some programs admit only through Quota 2. The chance of admission is not influenced by the rank of preference.

name: Denmark
about: Coordinated admission in Denmark only applies to Copenhagen, where students are assured a place in the schools in their district. Families can apply to two other schools. Siblings have placement priority, while pupils with language difficulties have reserved places. Other allocation criteria include linguistic balance, proximity and municipal residence.

name: Dominican Republic

name: Algeria
about: Algeria has a coordinated system for tertiary education. Applicants can rank from 6 to 10 options, including at least two local or regionally registered courses. Assignment criteria consider preferences, diploma scores, vacancies, and the student's desired district. Assigned students undergo oral interviews.

name: Algeria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Ecuador
about: Ecuador operates a coordinated system for its public universities, which involves several rounds of vacancy assignments. Starting from the second round, available slots are those declined by students in earlier rounds. Once students reject their initial placement choice, they are ineligible for subsequent rounds. Notably, in 2021, the system reduced the number of preferences allowed from 5 to 3.

name: Ecuador
about: Ecuador has a coordinated system for primary and secondary education. For students entering the first and second years of elementary school in institutions where demand exceeds capacity, the highest authority will conduct a public lottery among the applicants.

name: Egypt
about: Admission to tertiary education is facilitated through two distinct coordinated systems, one for public universities and the other for private ones. Private universities withdrew from the public admission system in 2021. Admission to public universities is solely based on the scores of the national secondary education leaving examination.

name: Spain
about: Since the 1980s, the Spanish autonomous communities have adopted coordinated admission systems. Each system varies according to the community, although all use the deferred acceptance mechanism. The ranking of students is determined by a score established by each managing organization.

name: Spain
about: In Spain, the assignment of students to public and private subsidized schools is governed by the Immediate Acceptance mechanism. Features common to all regions include the possibility for students to choose several schools and the priority given to factors such as siblings, proximity, and academic records. Tie-breaking criteria such as lotteries or academic scores are often employed.

name: Finland
about: The application process is split into multiple rounds.There are three joint applications per year, two that offer study programs in English (one in spring and one in autumn) and one that offer study programs only in Finnish and Swedish (in spring). The English - spring application period is the only one that does not provide a single allocation. Each program may require a entrance examination.

about: In the UK, different regions have different coordinated admissions systems. School admissions in all UK regions prioritize factors such as proximity, siblings and special needs.

name: Georgia
about: Georgia's coordinated system has unified national examinations for all institutions. Before the exams, applicants designate their preferred programs of study. At first, an applicant's score is compared to others who selected the same program as their first choice. If the student is not accepted, her scores are ranked consecutively with those who applied for every subsequent choice.

name: Ghana
about: Ghana has a coordinated system at the country level for all secondary institutions. At the end of junior high school, students take the basic education certification examination and those with high enough grades qualify for senior high school. The system aims to address socio-economic inequality, scaling up test scores for students from low-resourced and rural schools.

name: Greece
about: Greece has a coordinated system for public universities. It employs a two-phase assignment mechanism. In the first phase, candidates may apply to a limited set of preferences (the limit is 10% of the number of vacancies in each field). Those not admitted in the first phase proceed to the second phase with unlimited choices from remaining seats.

name: Hong Kong
about: The coordinated system comprises two stages. In the first one, uncoordinated applications prioritize family connections. Unsuccessful applicants proceed to the coordinated stage, where 10% of vacancies allow unrestricted school choices (up to 3 schools in or outside the school net), and the remaining 90% involve restricted school choices (up to 30 schools within the school net).

name: Hong Kong
about: The coordinated system is the main route designed to assist students with the secondary examination (HKDSE) results. Assignment will be based mainly on HKDSE, while other factors will be considered. The system employs a mix of DA and Boston mechanisms, temporarily cutting off applications after assigning seats to first-choice applicants and then a final allocation based on the DA algorithm.

name: Croatia
about: Croatia has a coordinated system for tertiary education. Applicants must fill in an application form to apply to any type of institution. Enrolment criteria are determined by institutions and include educational qualifications, previous achievements, and additional entrance exams. A candidate can be enrolled in two double major programs from the same university based on priorities and vacancies.

name: Hungary
about: Enrollment into secondary schools has been organized at the national level via a coordinated system. Students may supply preference lists of any length. Schools also rank applicants and this ranking is based on grades from the primary school, entrance exams (organized by the schools) and interviews. The weight of each score is decided by the school, under some constraints given in the regulation.

name: Hungary
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Indonesia
about: The high school admission system (called PPDB) is coordinated at the city level. Systems tend to have 4 channels. Zoning path: for students living in the school zone. Achievement path: prioritize students based on academic performance. Parent transfer path: for students not living in the school zone. Affirmative path: for students who come from economically disadvantaged families.

name: Indonesia
about: Indonesia's student admission methods, from Bandung's multiple tracks to Palembang's single-choice system, showcase the country's diverse local educational approaches. These variations reflect Indonesia's decentralized education system, which is tailored to meet the unique needs and priorities of each city.

name: India
about: Multiple regions in India have the Right to Education program, which determines 25% of vacancies in private schools. This system gives priority to disadvantaged groups based on income, caste and other criteria. Many regions also have coordinated systems for public schools, where priority tends to be given to siblings and those living near the school.

name: India
about: Multiple regions in India have the Right to Education program, which determines 25% of vacancies in private schools. This system gives priority to disadvantaged groups based on income, caste and other criteria. Many regions also have coordinated systems for public schools, where priority tends to be given to siblings and those living near the school.

name: Ireland
about: Ireland has a national system that has three rounds: A, Zero, and One. Round One is the main round. There are three types of undergraduate degrees: level 6, 7 and 8. Level 6 and 7 are applied through a unique list, while level 8 courses are applied through another list. Applicants can choose up to 10 programs on each list and can receive an offer from both lists.

name: Ireland
about: Ireland has a coordinated system for secondary schools at the Limerick Area. Each school sets its own criteria, such as catchment areas, religion, and sibling attendance. The first-choice school decides whether to accept the applicant and, if rejected, the application moves on to the next choices, resembling the Boston algorithm.

name: Iran
about: The system uses a scoring system based on the Konkour examination. This high-stakes, standardized test, in combination with GPA from their final 3 years of high school, determines their eligibility and rank for university admission. The allocation mechanism corresponds to the serial dictatorship mechanism. The system introduced criteria to encourage local enrollment.

name: Iraq
about: Iraq operates a coordinated system at the national level (excluding the Kurdistan region). Placement is based on Baccalaureate examination scores and vacancies. The number of program choices depends on the specialty, ranging from 10 to 50 choices. 10% of vacancies are for martyrs' families.

name: Israel
about: In Israel, coordinated admission operates in the Netanya region, which includes state, religious, Haredi and unofficial recognized schools. Enrollment for first grade is done annually through the municipal website, where they can indicate a maximum of 3 preferences. Priority is given based on proximity to the school, with special priorities for anchor schools and "space super-schools".

name: Israel
about: In Israel, both Netanya and Tel-Aviv employ distinct approaches to secondary school registrations. In Netanya, the municipal administration manages the process, allowing students to select up to three school preferences. Meanwhile, Tel-Aviv introduced its School Choice Program in 1994, where sixth-grade students rank preferences among three district schools and two outside options.

name: Italy
about: Italy has a coordinated system at the national level for primary and secondary public schools. Admission criteria are determined by each school; there are no national-level guidelines for admission criteria.

name: Japan
about: In Japan, there has been a shift from a traditional "school district system" to a "school selection system". Managed by the Municipal Education Boards, school assignment is now based on their preferences. The number of options varies by municipality, ranging from city-wide options to zone selections. In some towns such as Yame, lotteries decide school assignment.

name: Kenya
about: Kenya has a coordinated system at the national level. The number of preferences allowed is determined by academic performance. Previous years’ cut-off points are provided to guide applicants during the application process. In cases of ties for the last available seat, several actions may be taken, including raising the cut-off mark, expanding admission capacity, or considering other factors.

name: South Korea
about: In Korea, school admission is coordinated at the city level. Daegu follows an allocation based on 50% preference and 50% residence. In Jeju, if the 1st choice is full, applicants are assigned to the 2nd choice and can go up to the 10th preference.

name: South Korea
about: The High School Equalization Policy (HSEP), which began in the mid-1990s, randomly assigns students to academic high schools in 28 cities. Seoul altered the HSEP in 2010, introducing a three-phase system that allows school choice based on a lottery. Outside Seoul, some areas allow preferences before random assignment, decided by local education districts.

name: Sri Lanka
about: Sri Lanka has a coordinated system for public schools. Applicants must list a minimum of six schools near their place of residence, including at least three provincial schools, with a maximum of 16 schools allowed. Students are classified into different types of seats that include categories like children of residents living near the school, siblings of current students, among others.

name: Lesotho
about: The transition to the first year of secondary school is made through a coordinated system. Applicants must fill a form including three schools of their choice, and applications are forwarded to first-preference secondary schools. Priority is given to students residing near the applied school. Admissions also consider student's academic portfolio from Grade 1 to 7.

name: Lithuania
about: Lithuania has various coordinated systems for primary and secondary schools. These systems vary depending on the region. The number of possible preferences to declare ranges from 2 to 4. While the systems vary, common admission priority points often include grades from previous courses or proximity to the school, and the vast majority of systems value having siblings in the institution.

name: Lithuania
about: Lithuania has various coordinated systems for primary and secondary schools. These systems vary depending on the region. The number of possible preferences to declare ranges from 2 to 4. While the systems vary, common admission priority points often include grades from previous courses or proximity to the school, and the vast majority of systems value having siblings in the institution.

name: Latvia
about: Latvia has a coordinated system for 12 participating universities. Applicants can choose up to 10 programs and 20 priorities. Priorities consist of the program, form of study (full or part-time), and funding. The process includes two rounds; the first round resembles a Boston mechanism (applicants can only be assigned to their first preference), while the second round has a DA mechanism.

name: Mexico
about: In several Mexican states such as Jalisco, Guanajuato, Baja California, Mexico City, Nuevo Leon and the State of Mexico, there are coordinated admission systems. Parents select preferred schools online and priority criteria often include proximity to the school and sibling attendance.

It's mandatory to include at least one non-selective course in the list of preferences. For selective training programs, such as university degrees, applicants are required to take specific tests.

name: Nigeria
about: Nigeria operates a coordinated system for secondary public schools. Candidates may apply to up to six schools, one from each geographic zone. Admission is based on the National Common Entrance Examination (60%), regional quotas (30%) and exigency (10%).

name: Nigeria
about: Nigeria has a coordinated system for all institutions. When students register for the Unified Tertiary Matriculation Examination (UTME), they can mention up to 4 program choices. Admission ranking is based on UTME scores, institutional screening scores, senior school grades, and interviews. Public universities have quotas based on merit, catchment area and for less educationally developed states.

In Amsterdam and Rotterdam, primary schools provide binding advice on where students should pursue their studies, restricting applications to schools that match this guidance. Three types of assignment algorithms are used: deferred acceptance, immediate acceptance, and serial dictatorship.

Eligible applicants must take and pass the specific Medical Entrance Examination. A merit list is generated based on eligibility and academic performance.

about: Papua New Guinea employs a coordinated system for tertiary education at the national level. The system moved from using an immediate acceptance mechanism to a deferred acceptance mechanism in 2018. Each program can set the selection criteria (GPA is set by default).

name: Poland
about: Poland has several coordinated systems for public secondary schools that vary from region to region. Among the mechanisms used, deferred acceptance is the most common. The maximum number of preferences varies from 3 to unlimited depending on the region.

name: Poland
about: Poland has several coordinated public school systems that vary according to cities and regions. Candidates can apply to three schools, which is guaranteed by the country's regulations. However, in some local administrations it is possible to apply to more than three schools. The number of preferences to declare varies and often has no feasible limits.

name: Puerto Rico
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Puerto Rico
about: Puerto Rico has a coordinated system for primary and secondary schools. Priority is given to students remaining in their current school, then to those seeking transfers based on their preferences. Families can list up to three schools per child.

name: Portugal
about: Portugal has a coordinated system for primary and secondary schools at the national level. Applicants can select up to five schools and their desired course. Priority is given to the first preference, with subsequent options considered if vacancies are unavailable. Tiebreaker criteria change among institutions.

name: Qatar
about: In Qatar, the Ministry of Education manages coordinated admission for public primary and secondary schools. The online platform enables parents to view school capacities, vacancies, and enroll students accordingly. Siblings receive priority in registration.

name: Rwanda
about: Rwanda has a coordinated system for students who have successfully passed the primary national examinations. Good performance is crucial because the system starts allocating the best performing students. Students are assigned to schools within their respective districts or in close proximity to their locations.

name: Sudan
about: Sudan's tertiary education admission follows a coordinated system with two rounds. Applicants order preferences, with admission based on secondary examination scores. Half of seats in disadvantaged states must be assign to students living in that state.

name: Singapore
about: Singapore has a coordinated system for public schools. If the number of applicants exceeds the number of vacancies, selection will be based on merit. The schools offer priority admission if listed as the first choice. Students not placed in preferred schools are allocated based on their exams scores and registered address. Tiebreaking rules include citizenship status and order of school choice.

name: Singapore
about: The coordinated system for public schools in Singapore follows several phases. These phases include considerations such as sibling connections, parent volunteerism, alumni affiliation, and home-school distance. Registrants are allowed to select only one school at each phase. If the number of applicants exceeds school vacancies, a random assignment is made.

name: Sierra Leone
about: Sierra Leona has a coordinated system for secondary public schools. Candidates can choose up to three schools, and placement is based on their choices and an entry exam. An algorithm considers available seats, prioritizing first-choice candidates. Interviews may follow for admission, with candidates not placed in their choices accommodated in the nearest available school.

name: Slovenia
about: Slovenia has a coordinated system for tertiary institutions at the national level. Candidates may specify a maximum of three different study programs in order of priority in which they wish to enroll. Selection criteria typically include final exam scores and overall academic performance in secondary school, with specific subject achievements also considered.

name: Slovenia
about: Slovenia operates a coordinated system for secondary schools. Candidates apply for enrollment in one educational program at one school. The selection process involves two rounds for programs with enrollment restrictions. In the first round, students are allocated based on academic performance.

name: Sweden
about: In regions like Gothenburg, Stockholm, Uppsala, and Vasteras, Sweden, coordinated systems manage secondary school admissions. Students rank their school preferences and compete based on their academic performance.

name: Sweden
about: University applications for all programs are coordinated through the Swedish Council for Higher Education. The process includes two rounds: one for English programs and another for Swedish programs. Applicants can choose up to eight programs. Each institution determines its own admission criteria. After considering on-time applicants, remaining spots are offered to waitlisted and late applicants.

name: Syria
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Syria
about: Syria has a coordinated system for scientific programs. Mofadala is a list describing the minimum scores required. After graduation exams, the Mofadala is published. Depending on this and applicants’ interests, they list fields in order. Then, the second Mofadala is published, which determines allocations. Students are assigned to the first field on their list in which they meet the minimum score.

name: Tunisia
about: Tunisia manages a coordinated system for public institutions. Applicants' selection is primarily based on their baccalaureate score, which considers GPA, grades in relevant subjects, and their location. Students can list multiple program choices, with a minimum requirement of six. The selection process involves several rounds, prioritizing candidates with higher scores in the first round.

name: Tunisia
about: In Tunisia, a coordinated system is employed for admission to twelve selective high schools across the country. The application process depends on the student's middle school district, with some students having limited choice based on their district. Applicants undergo selection based on their performance in the national end-of-middle-school exam.

name: Turkey
about: Turkey has a coordinated system for tertiary education. A student’s results from the tests basic proficiency (40%) and field qualification (60%), are combined with their grades to calculate a final score. After students have received their results, they indicate their preferences for up to 24 programs via a coordinated system which automatically assigns applicants to a bachelor’s program.

name: Turkey
about: Turkey has a coordinated system for public schools. The system covers three types of schools: central exam, local placement, and boarding. Students apply to all three simultaneously. If students are assigned to a central exam school (using a serial dictatorship mechanism) and accept, other two types will not be considered. The same is true between local placement and boarding school preferences.

name: Tanzania
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Tanzania
about: In Tanzania, tertiary education admission is facilitated through a coordinated online system. Applicants can select up to five institutions and will eventually be assigned to one of their choices.

name: Uganda
about: This country lacks a coordinated system.

name: Uganda
about: Uganda has a coordinated system for government-sponsored seats at public universities. Admission pathways include the national merit quota and the district quota, with 25% of seats allocated via district quotas to address regional inequalities. There exists a bonus point system for women's participation. Unsuccessful applicants in the first round can reapply under private sponsorship.

name: Uruguay
about: Uruguay implements a national coordinated system for school admissions. Families must register three preferred institutions during the application process for public high schools. The first option is determined based on proximity, considering the school the student has historically attended. For the other two options, families have the flexibility to select the institution of their choice.

name: United States
about: In the U.S., cities such as Boston, Chicago, Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles, New York, San Antonio and San Diego apply various school choice systems. These systems use priority criteria such as proximity, sibling enrollment and use lotteries to distribute places in preferred schools. The range of school choice usually varies from 5 to 14 options.

name: Vietnam

Nowadays, candidates do not need to choose a method, because the system will consider the method with the highest chance of acceptance.
